>her "canon end"
Ouch. I mean, I'm all for a realistic wrap to a characters rough & hard life. But, it does restrict adding new lore by having to work within such constraints. A pretty hard binary decision would need to be made here: pick up her story including a timeline with the injuries depicted and all the baggage that goes with it

Or, retcon out her current ending to at least extend her timeline before meeting this part of her fate & karma. And with that, delay a decision on meeting this particular ending at all, or a modified version of it.

There's a whole bit of world-building behind all of that, including trying to keep her in her original world as much as possible, or recreating a new similar world.

Opening her to pubic domain is one decent idea, if you're sure you're willing to do that. A number of other characters have had successful "careers" by that method.

If you're willing to go that route, consider designing a Creative Commons license, and decide how much input you want on who & how & under what circumstances others may use or borrow her. As the original creator, you can retain some control over what is official canon for her, if you want to. There are lots of options and easy ways to accomplish them:

https://creativecommons.org/licenses/

I used to do a bit of this in the music industry and it's a very solid model that's been around for quite a while. Well worth considering.

Anonymous Tue 07 Dec 2021 17:02:15 No.43778856 Report
Quoted By:
>>43778531
>The creative commons thing is neat.
Yes. It is. Of course it's up to you, but I urge investing some time looking into it. It's not all that complex, they try to keep it in plain language that is still legally binding so Normal People can use it globally around the Internets & the world.

>I dunno if i wanna make it super official though?
Again, your choice. What you're sort of looking at is attempting to be a gatekeeper on your Intellectual Property. You give up as much as you wish to, within public domain use.

Because Public Domain means you already are gifting your content to the world, of course you will never have full control again. But you can retain certain controls, the most important of which is: Yes, you may use this IP, but you may not profit off it without a separate and specific legal contract with me. And, you cannot hide the derivative content from the world: it must be Public Domain also

And details you need to delve into on the Creative Commons site to make that happen, and variations on it.

The reason I post this is: Develop a Creative Commons model that you like so that you can use it whenever you wish with ANYTHING you create. It protects your content from being stolen, and forces people to come to you for specific contracts if they want to use part of your content for business/merch/whatever. Everyone else can use it like any greentext on /trash/ because it's fair use for fans.

Don't think of this as a project for Roxanne. It's a project for every aspect of your work. Releasing your work into the wild is advertisement for people to enjoy freely, but they come back to you to negotiate licensing fees for sales. Every art, music, and text you create.

Hope that helps you out in some way. As I said, I helped a lot of musicians start up with this model. We torrented recordings their shows for free, which built a fanbase that bootstrapped into sales of higher quality finished product, plus gigs to play bars & other venues.
